# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fragment-based-drug-discovery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The dissociation constant is the inverse of the association constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] In the special case of salts, the dissociation constant can also be called an ionization constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] where [A], [B], and [A*x* B*y*] are the equilibrium concentrations of A, B, and the complex A*x* B*y*, respectively.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] That is, *K*D, which has the dimensions of concentration, equals the concentration of free A at which half of the total molecules of B are associated with A.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This simple interpretation does not apply for higher values of *x* or *y*.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] It also presumes the absence of competing reactions, though the derivation can be extended to explicitly allow for and describe competitive binding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] It is useful as a quick description of the binding of a substance, in the same way that EC50 and IC50 describe the biological activities of substances.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Experimentally, the concentration of the molecule complex [AB] is obtained indirectly from the measurement of the concentration of a free molecules, either [A] or [B].
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] In principle, the total amounts of molecule [A]0 and [B]0 added to the reaction are known.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Many biological proteins and enzymes can possess more than one binding site.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Usually, when a ligand L binds with a macromolecule M, it can influence binding kinetics of other ligands L binding to the macromolecule.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] A simplified mechanism can be formulated if the affinity of all binding sites can be considered independent of the number of ligands bound to the macromolecule.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This is valid for macromolecules composed of more than one, mostly identical, subunits.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] It can be then assumed that each of these n subunits are identical, symmetric and that they possess only a single binding site.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Even when the microscopic dissociation constant is the same for each individual binding event, the macroscopic outcome (*K′*1, *K′*2 and *K′*3) is not equal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This can be understood intuitively for our example of three possible binding sites.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] *K′*1 describes the reaction from one state (no ligand bound) to three states (one ligand bound to either of the three binding sides).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The apparent *K′*1 would therefore be three times smaller than the individual *K*D.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] *K′*2 describes the reaction from three states (one ligand bound) to three states (two ligands bound); therefore, *K′*2 would be equal to *K*D.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] *K′*3 describes the reaction from three states (two ligands bound) to one state (three ligands bound); hence, the apparent dissociation constant *K′*3 is three times bigger than the microscopic dissociation constant *K*D.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The dissociation constant is commonly used to describe the affinity between a ligand ${\ce {L}}$ (such as a drug) and a protein ${\ce {P}}$ ; i.e., how tightly a ligand binds to a particular protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Ligand–protein affinities are influenced by non-covalent intermolecular interactions between the two molecules such as hydrogen bonding, electrostatic interactions, hydrophobic and van der Waals forces.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Affinities can also be affected by high concentrations of other macromolecules, which causes macromolecular crowding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] where ${\ce {[P], [L]}}$ , and ${\ce {[LP]}}$ represent molar concentrations of the protein, ligand, and protein–ligand complex, respectively.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The smaller the dissociation constant, the more tightly bound the ligand is, or the higher the affinity between ligand and protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] For example, a ligand with a nanomolar (nM) dissociation constant binds more tightly to a particular protein than a ligand with a micromolar (μM) dissociation constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Sub-picomolar dissociation constants as a result of non-covalent binding interactions between two molecules are rare.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Nevertheless, there are some important exceptions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Biotin and avidin bind with a dissociation constant of roughly 10−15 M = 1 fM = 0.000001 nM.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Ribonuclease inhibitor proteins may also bind to ribonuclease with a similar 10−15 M affinity.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The dissociation constant for a particular ligand–protein interaction can change with solution conditions (e.g., temperature, pH and salt concentration).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The effect of different solution conditions is to effectively modify the strength of any intermolecular interactions holding a particular ligand–protein complex together.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Drugs can produce harmful side effects through interactions with proteins for which they were not meant to or designed to interact.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Therefore, much pharmaceutical research is aimed at designing drugs that bind to only their target proteins (negative design) with high affinity (typically 0.1–10 nM) or at improving the affinity between a particular drug and its *in vivo* protein target (positive design).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] In the specific case of antibodies (Ab) binding to antigen (Ag), usually the term **affinity constant** refers to the association constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This chemical equilibrium is also the ratio of the on-rate (*k*forward or *k*a) and off-rate (*k*back or *k*d) constants.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Two antibodies can have the same affinity, but one may have both a high on- and off-rate constant, while the other may have both a low on- and off-rate constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] For the deprotonation of acids, *K* is known as *K*a, the acid dissociation constant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] Strong acids, such as sulfuric or phosphoric acid, have large dissociation constants; weak acids, such as acetic acid, have small dissociation constants.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The symbol *K*a, used for the acid dissociation constant, can lead to confusion with the association constant, and it may be necessary to see the reaction or the equilibrium expression to know which is meant.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This $\mathrm {p} K$ notation is seen in other contexts as well; it is mainly used for covalent dissociations (i.e., reactions in which chemical bonds are made or broken) since such dissociation constants can vary greatly.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] A molecule can have several acid dissociation constants.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] In this regard, that is depending on the number of the protons they can give up, we define *monoprotic*, *diprotic* and *triprotic* acids.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The first (e.g., acetic acid or ammonium) have only one dissociable group, the second (e.g., carbonic acid, bicarbonate, glycine) have two dissociable groups and the third (e.g., phosphoric acid) have three dissociable groups.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] In the case of multiple p*K* values they are designated by indices: p*K*1, p*K*2, p*K*3 and so on.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] For amino acids, the p*K*1 constant refers to its carboxyl (–COOH) group, p*K*2 refers to its amino (–NH2) group and the p*K*3 is the p*K* value of its side chain.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The concentration of water, [H2O], is omitted by convention, which means that the value of *K*w differs from the value of *K*eq that would be computed using that concentration.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] The value of *K*w varies with temperature, as shown in the table below.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/dissociation-constant] This variation must be taken into account when making precise measurements of quantities such as pH.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] In analogy to the rule of five, it has been proposed that ideal fragments should follow the 'rule of three' (molecular weight < 300, ClogP < 3, the number of hydrogen bond donors and acceptors each should be < 3 and the number of rotatable bonds should be < 3).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] Since the fragments have relatively low affinity for their targets, they must have high water solubility so that they can be screened at higher concentrations.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] In fragment-based drug discovery, the low binding affinities of the fragments pose significant challenges for screening.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] Many biophysical techniques have been applied to address this issue.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] At modern X-ray crystallography synchrotron beamlines, several hundred data sets of protein-ligand complex crystal structures can be obtained within 24 hours.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] This technology makes crystallographic fragment screening possible, i.e. the use of X-ray crystallography directly for the fragment screening step.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] Once a fragment (or a combination of fragments) have been identified, protein X-ray crystallography is used to obtain structural models of the protein-fragment(s) complexes.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] Such information can then be used to guide organic synthesis for high-affinity protein ligands and enzyme inhibitors.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/fragment-based-lead-discovery] Advantages of screening low molecular weight fragment based libraries over traditional higher molecular weight chemical libraries are several.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In chemical thermodynamics, **isothermal titration calorimetry** (**ITC**) is a physical technique used to determine the thermodynamic parameters of interactions in solution.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] It consists of two cells which are enclosed in an adiabatic jacket.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The compounds to be studied are placed in the sample cell, while the other cell, the reference cell, is used as a control and contains the buffer in which the sample is dissolved.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The technique quantifies the heat released or absorbed during the binding process by incrementally adding one reactant (via a syringe) to another (in the sample cell) while maintaining constant temperature and pressure.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Heat-sensing devices within the ITC detect temperature variations between two cells, transmitting this information to heaters that adjust accordingly to restore thermal equilibrium between the cells.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This energy is converted into binding enthalpy using the information about concentrations of the reactants and the cell volume.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Compared to other calorimeters, ITC does not require any correctors since there is no heat exchange between the system and the environment.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC is also highly sensitive with a fast response time and benefits from modest sample requirements.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] While differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) can also provide direct information about the thermodynamic of binding interactions, ITC offers the added capability of quantifying the thermodynamics of metal ion binding to proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The history of ITC can be traced back to the 1930s when isothermal calorimetry was used to study chemical reactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In 1965 Christensen and Izatt introduced titration calorimetry as a method for simultaneously determining the equilibrium constant and enthalpy.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The ITC technique was then developed by H.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Johnston in 1968 as a part of his Ph.D. dissertation at Brigham Young University, and was considered niche until introduced commercially by MicroCal Inc. in 1988.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Originally, ITC was most often used to study the binding of small molecules (such as medicinal compounds) to larger macromolecules (proteins, DNA etc.) in a label-free environment.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Its application has now broadened, aided by modern improvements, making it possible to measure the heat effects as small as 0.1 μcal (0.4 μJ) and determine the binding constants (K) as high as 108–109 M−1.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC is a quantitative technique that can determine the binding affinity ( $K_{a}$ ), reaction enthalpy ( $\Delta H$ ), and binding stoichiometry ( n ) of the interaction between two or more molecules in solution.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This is achieved by measuring the enthalpies of a series of binding reactions caused by injections of a solution of one molecule to a reaction cell containing a solution of another molecule.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The enthalpy values are plotted over the molar ratios resulting from the injections.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] From the plot, the molar reaction enthalpy $\Delta H$ , the affinity constant ( $K_{a}$ ) and the stochiometry are determined by curve fitting.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] (where R is the gas constant and T is the absolute temperature).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] For accurate measurements of binding affinity, the curve of the thermogram must be sigmoidal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] A steep sigmoidal curve signals a strong binding whereas a less steep sigmoidal curve points to a weaker binding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] where n is the stoichiometry of the binding, $K_{a}$ is the association constant and M is the concentration of the molecule in the cell.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The c-value must fall between 1 and 1000, ideally between 10 and 100.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In terms of binding affinity, it would be approximately from $1.0\times 10^{3}$ ~ $10^{7}$ within the limit range.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] If it does not fall within the above range, the thermodynamic values obtained from the experiment are less robust to interpretation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] An isothermal titration calorimeter is composed of two identical cells made of a highly efficient thermally conducting and chemically inert material such as Hastelloy alloy or gold, surrounded by an adiabatic jacket.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In this setup, one of the cells, the sample cell, holds the solution of one reactant, and the other cell, the reference cell, is filled with either a buffer or water.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The second reactant, which has a higher concentration than the first, is placed in a syringe and gradually injected into the sample cell in small aliquots throughout the titration process.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This process is semi-automated and the sensitive thermopile/thermocouple circuits are used to detect temperature differences between the reference cell (filled with buffer or water) and the sample cell containing the macromolecule.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Prior to addition of ligand, a constant power (<1 mW) is applied to the reference cell.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This directs a feedback circuit, activating a heater located on the sample cell.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] During the experiment, ligand is titrated into the sample cell in precisely known aliquots, causing heat to be either taken up or evolved (depending on the nature of the reaction).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Measurements consist of the time-dependent input of power required to maintain equal temperatures between the sample and reference cells.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In an exothermic reaction, the temperature in the sample cell increases upon addition of ligand.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This causes the feedback power to the sample cell to be decreased (remember: a reference power is applied to the reference cell) in order to maintain an equal temperature between the two cells.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In an endothermic reaction, the opposite occurs; the feedback circuit increases the power in order to maintain a constant temperature (isothermal operation).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Observations are plotted as the power needed to maintain the reference and the sample cell at an identical temperature against time.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] As a result, the experimental raw data consists of a series of spikes of heat flow (power), with every spike corresponding to one ligand injection.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] These heat flow spikes/pulses are integrated with respect to time, giving the total heat exchanged per injection.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] By integrating each peak from the baseline, the total heat associated with each injection is obtained, including both reaction-specific and non-reaction-related contributions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The pattern of these heat effects as a function of the molar ratio [ligand]/[macromolecule] can then be analyzed to give the thermodynamic parameters of the interaction under study.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In order to accurately and precisely measure the thermodynamic parameters using ITC, certain procedures must be followed, involving instrument set up, parameter configuration, sample loading, buffer selection, and instrument cleaning.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] To obtain an optimum result, each injection should be given enough time for a reaction equilibrium to reach.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Degassing samples is often necessary in order to obtain good measurements as the presence of gas bubbles within the sample cell will lead to abnormal data plots in the recorded results.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The entire experiment takes place under computer control.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Direct titration is performed most commonly with ITC to obtain the thermodynamic data, by binding two components of the reaction directly to each other.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] However, many of the chemical reactions and binding interactions may have higher binding affinity above what is desirable with the c-window.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] To troubleshoot the limitation of c-window and conditions for certain binding interactions, various different methods of titration can be performed.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In some cases, simply doing a reverse titration of changing the samples between the injection syringe and sample cell can solve the issue, depending on the binding mechanism.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] However, the process of introducing a ligand to a macromolecule is distinct from the process of adding a macromolecule to a ligand.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] While the binding equilibrium remains unchanged in both direct and reverse titrations, the route to equilibrium and the accessible binding states varies, particularly when one molecule possesses multiple binding sites for the other.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Most of the high or low affinity bindings require chelation or competitive titration.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This method is done by loading pre-bound complex solution in the sample cell and chelating one of the components out with a reagent of higher observed binding affinity within the desirable c-window.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In order to ensure optimum instrument stability, the ITC instrument should be powered on at least one day before use.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Samples should ideally be pre-equilibrated to approximately 2 °C below the target experimental temperature to reduce stabilization time after loading, although starting at the exact experimental temperature is also an option.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] For instrument cleaning, sample cell should be rinsed with the experimental buffer and dried under vacuum, and any remaining rinsed solution should be discarded manually with a syringe.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Then, the sample cell is filled with the experimental solution and the reference cell with either high-purity water or the same buffer.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] To prevent air contamination, gas-tight Hamilton syringes are used, ensuring the needle is positioned near the bottom of the sample cell before dispensing the liquid slowly.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Experimental parameters such as the number of injections, initial injection volume, subsequent injection volumes, temperature, reference power, stirring speed, spacing, initial delay, and filter period should be adjusted according to the specific study.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] If the experiment is to be repeated, the syringe should be emptied, with the solution either discarded or saved for further analysis.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Before refilling with the same solution, the syringe needle should be externally rinsed and dried with lint-free paper, without the need for an internal wash.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] However, when switching to a different reagent or concentration, the syringe must be thoroughly washed, flushed with ethanol or methanol, and carefully dried under vacuum-using a ThermoVac for VP-ITC or the integrated vacuum systems in other models.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The sample cell should be emptied using the loading syringe and rinsed multiple times with water.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] It is necessary to conduct a post-hoc analysis to determine the buffer or solvent-independent enthalpy from the experimental thermodynamics.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The collected experimental data reflects not only the binding thermodynamics of the interaction of interest, but any contributing competing equilibria associated to it.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] A post-hoc analysis can be performed to determine the buffer or solvent-independent enthalpy from the experimental thermodynamics, by simply going through the process of Hess' law.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Below example shows a simple interaction between a metal ion (M) and a ligand (L).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] B represents the buffer used for this interaction and ${\ce {H+}}$ represents protons.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] which can be further processed to calculate the enthalpy of metal-ligand interaction.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Although this example is between a metal and a ligand, it is applicable to any ITC experiment, regarding binding interactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] As a part of the analysis, a number of protons are required to calculate the solvent-independent thermodynamics.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This can be easily done by plotting a graph such as shown below.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Equilibrium constant of the reaction is also not independent from the other competing equilibria.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Competition would include buffer interactions and other pH-dependent reactions depending on the experimental conditions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] For the past 30 years, isothermal titration calorimetry has been used in a wide array of fields, ranging from metal binding studies to drug discovery, and nanomaterials research.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In the old days, this technique was used to determine fundamental thermodynamic values for basic small molecular interactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In recent years, ITC has been used in more industrially applicable areas, such as drug discovery and testing synthetic materials.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Although it is still heavily used in fundamental chemistry, the trend has shifted over to the biological side, where label-free and buffer independent values are relatively harder to achieve.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Using the thermodynamic data from ITC, it is possible to deduce enzyme kinetics including proton or electron transfer, allostery and cooperativity, and enzyme inhibition.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Modern ITC instruments can measure heat rates as small as 0.1 μcal/sec, allowing for the precise determination of reaction rates in the range of 10−12 mol/sec and ITC can determine values for Km and kcat, in the ranges of 10−2–103 μM and 0.05–500 sec−1, respectively.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC collects data over time that is useful for any kinetic experiments, but especially with the proteins due to constant aliquots of injections.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] In terms of calculation, equilibrium constant and the slopes of binding can be directly utilized to determine the allostery and charge transfer, by comparing experimental data of different conditions (pH, use of mutated peptide chain and binding sites, etc.).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Kinetic data obtained from ITC have been found to closely align with results from other purely kinetic methods, such as surface plasmon resonance.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Membrane proteins and self-assembly properties of certain proteins can be studied under this technique, due to being a label-free calorimeter.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Membrane proteins are known to have difficulties with selection of proper solubilization and purification protocols.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] As ITC is a non-destructive calorimetric tool, it can be used as a detector to locate the fraction of protein with desired binding sites, by binding a known binding ligand to the protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This feature also applies in studies of self-assembling proteins, especially in use of measuring thermodynamics of their structural transformation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC can provide insights into drug development by charactering the affinity, selectivity, ligand-induced conformational changes, and drug partitioning into membranes.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Binding affinity carries a huge importance in medicinal chemistry, as drugs need to bind to the protein effectively within a desired range.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] An exothermic binding process with a favorable enthalpy is considered a desirable characteristic for specific protein binders, as it indicates strong potential for optimization and high selectivity.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] However, determining enthalpy changes and optimization of thermodynamic parameters are hugely difficult when designing drugs.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC troubleshoots this issue easily by deducing the binding affinity, enthalpic/entropic contributions and its binding stoichiometry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Applying the ideas above, chirality of organometallic compounds can be deduced as well with this technique.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Each chiral compound has its own unique properties and binding mechanisms that are comparable to each other, which leads to differences in thermodynamic properties.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] By binding chiral solutions in a binding site can deduce the type of chirality and depending on the purpose, which chiral compound is more suitable for binding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Binding metal ions to protein and other components of biological material is one of the most popular uses of ITC, since ovotransferrin to ferric iron binding study published by Lin et al. from MicroCal Inc.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] This is due to some of the metal ions utilized in biological systems having d10 electron configuration which cannot be studied with other common techniques such as UV-vis spectrophotometry or electron paramagnetic resonance.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] It is also closely related to biochemical and medicinal studies due to the large abundance of metal binding enzymes in biological systems.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] The technique has been well utilized in studying carbon nanotubes to determine thermodynamic binding interactions with biological molecules and graphene composite interactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Another notable use of ITC with carbon nanotubes is optimization of preparation of carbon nanotubes from graphene composite and polyvinyl alcohol (PVA).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] PVA assembly process can be measured thermodynamically as mixing of the two ingredients is an exothermic reaction, and its binding trend can be easily observed by ITC.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC is increasingly utilized to study protein-nanoparticle interactions by providing key insights into binding affinity (in the form of association constant), interaction mechanisms (quantified through binding enthalpy, binding entropy, and Gibbs free energy), and binding stoichiometry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] These thermodynamic parameters from ITC can help assess structural modifications in proteins upon adsorption onto nanoparticle surfaces.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] One of the main limitations of ITC is that it is prone to allowing only moderate binding conformations to be detected, making it less effective for detecting very weak or extremely tight binding events.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Hence, it may struggle to provide accurate thermodynamic parameters for slow kinetic processes with long time constants, as these interactions may be masked by baseline noise and variability.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] On the other hand, high-affinity interactions can be challenging to measure if they take several minutes or longer to fully develop, or if the measured signal depends on the reaction enthalpy.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] When the binding enthalpy is close to zero, ITC may fail to generate meaningful interaction data, instead producing a series of small, uniform peaks that result in flat and uninformative thermograms.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] ITC is also susceptible to interference from unrelated heat signals, making it difficult to isolate and interpret the heat changes associated with the interaction of interest.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/isothermal-titration-calorimetry] Other limitations include solubility constraints, challenges in accurately determining protein concentration and the need to prepare the ligand in the same solution conditions as the protein for reliable measurements.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] Ligand efficiency is used in drug discovery research programs to assist in narrowing focus to lead compounds with optimal combinations of physicochemical properties and pharmacological properties.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] where Δ*G* = −*RT*ln*Ki* and *N* is the number of non-hydrogen atoms.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] PEI is a relative measure for comparing compounds tested in the same conditions (e.g. a single-point assay) and are not comparable at different inhibitor concentrations.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] Also for BEI and SEI, similar measurements must be used (e.g. always using pKi).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] where pKi, pKd and pIC50 is defined as −log(Ki), −log(Kd), or −log(IC 50), respectively.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] The authors suggest plotting compounds SEI and BEI on a plane and optimizing compounds towards the diagonal and so optimizing both SEI and BEI which incorporate potency, molecular weight and PSA.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/ligand-efficiency] Group efficiency (GE) is a metric used to estimate the binding efficiency of groups added to a ligand.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The surface plasmon polariton is a non-radiative electromagnetic surface wave that propagates in a direction parallel to the negative permittivity/dielectric material interface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Since the wave is on the boundary of the conductor and the external medium (air, water or vacuum for example), these oscillations are very sensitive to any change of this boundary, such as the adsorption of molecules to the conducting surface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] To describe the existence and properties of surface plasmon polaritons, one can choose from various models (quantum theory, Drude model, etc.).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The simplest way to approach the problem is to treat each material as a homogeneous continuum, described by a frequency-dependent relative permittivity between the external medium and the surface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This quantity, hereafter referred to as the materials' "dielectric function", is the complex permittivity.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In order for the terms that describe the electronic surface plasmon to exist, the real part of the dielectric constant of the conductor must be negative and its magnitude must be greater than that of the dielectric.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This condition is met in the infrared-visible wavelength region for air/metal and water/metal interfaces (where the real dielectric constant of a metal is negative and that of air or water is positive).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] LSPRs (localized surface plasmon resonances) are collective electron charge oscillations in metallic nanoparticles that are excited by light.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] They exhibit enhanced near-field amplitude at the resonance wavelength.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This field is highly localized at the nanoparticle and decays rapidly away from the nanoparticle/dielectric interface into the dielectric background, though far-field scattering by the particle is also enhanced by the resonance.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Light intensity enhancement is a very important aspect of LSPRs and localization means the LSPR has very high spatial resolution (subwavelength), limited only by the size of nanoparticles.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Because of the enhanced field amplitude, effects that depend on the amplitude such as magneto-optical effect are also enhanced by LSPRs.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In order to excite surface plasmon polaritons in a resonant manner, one can use electron bombardment or incident light beam (visible and infrared are typical).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The incoming beam has to match its momentum to that of the plasmon.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In the case of p-polarized light (polarization occurs parallel to the plane of incidence), this is possible by passing the light through a block of glass to increase the wavenumber (and the momentum), and achieve the resonance at a given wavelength and angle.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] S-polarized light (polarization occurs perpendicular to the plane of incidence) cannot excite electronic surface plasmons.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] where k( $\omega$ ) is the wave vector, $\varepsilon$ is the relative permittivity, and $\mu$ is the relative permeability of the material (1: the glass block, 2: the metal film), while $\omega$ is angular frequency and ${c}$ is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Typical metals that support surface plasmons are silver and gold, but metals such as copper, titanium or chromium have also been used.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When using light to excite SP waves, there are two configurations which are well known.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In the **Otto configuration**, the light illuminates the wall of a glass block, typically a prism, and is totally internally reflected.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] A thin metal film (for example gold) is positioned close enough to the prism wall so that an evanescent wave can interact with the plasma waves on the surface and hence excite the plasmons.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In the **Kretschmann configuration** (also known as **Kretschmann–Raether configuration**), the metal film is evaporated onto the glass block.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The light again illuminates the glass block, and an evanescent wave penetrates through the metal film.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The plasmons are excited at the outer side of the film.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This configuration is used in most practical applications.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When the surface plasmon wave interacts with a local particle or irregularity, such as a rough surface, part of the energy can be re-emitted as light.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This emitted light can be detected *behind* the metal film from various directions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Surface plasmon resonance can be implemented in analytical instrumentation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] SPR instruments consist of a light source, an input scheme, a prism with analyte interface, a detector, and computer.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Any quantitative derivation relies on modelling the surface based on the boundary conditions of the Maxwell's equations, for plane films using the Fresnel equations.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The detectors used in surface plasmon resonance convert the photons of light reflected off the metallic film into an electrical signal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] A position sensing detector (PSD) or charged-coupled device (CCD) may be used to operate as detectors.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Surface plasmons have been used to enhance the surface sensitivity of several spectroscopic measurements including fluorescence, Raman scattering, and second-harmonic generation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In their simplest form, SPR reflectivity measurements can be used to detect molecular adsorption, such as polymers, DNA or proteins, etc.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Technically, it is common to measure the angle of minimum reflection (angle of maximum absorption).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This angle changes in the order of 0.1° during thin (about nm thickness) film adsorption.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] (See also the Examples.) In other cases the changes in the absorption wavelength is followed.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The mechanism of detection is based on the adsorbing molecules causing changes in the local index of refraction, changing the resonance conditions of the surface plasmon waves.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The same principle is exploited in the recently developed competitive platform based on loss-less dielectric multilayers (DBR), supporting surface electromagnetic waves with sharper resonances (Bloch surface waves).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] If the surface is patterned with different biopolymers, using adequate optics and imaging sensors (i.e. a camera), the technique can be extended to surface plasmon resonance imaging (SPRI).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This method provides a high contrast of the images based on the adsorbed amount of molecules, somewhat similar to Brewster angle microscopy (this latter is most commonly used together with a Langmuir–Blodgett trough).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] For nanoparticles, localized surface plasmon oscillations can give rise to the intense colors of suspensions or sols containing the nanoparticles.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Nanoparticles or nanowires of noble metals exhibit strong absorption bands in the ultraviolet–visible light regime that are not present in the bulk metal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This extraordinary absorption increase has been exploited to increase light absorption in photovoltaic cells by depositing metal nanoparticles on the cell surface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The energy (color) of this absorption differs when the light is polarized along or perpendicular to the nanowire.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Shifts in this resonance due to changes in the local index of refraction upon adsorption to the nanoparticles can also be used to detect biopolymers such as DNA or proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Related complementary techniques include plasmon waveguide resonance, QCM, extraordinary optical transmission, and dual-polarization interferometry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The first SPR immunoassay was proposed in 1983 by Liedberg, Nylander, and Lundström, then of the Linköping Institute of Technology (Sweden).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] They adsorbed human IgG onto a 600-Ångström silver film, and used the assay to detect anti-human IgG in water solution.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Unlike many other immunoassays, such as ELISA, an SPR immunoassay is *label free* in that a label molecule is not required for detection of the analyte.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Additionally, the measurements on SPR can be followed real-time allowing the monitoring of individual steps in sequential binding events particularly useful in the assessment of for instance sandwich complexes.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Multi-parametric surface plasmon resonance, a special configuration of SPR, can be used to characterize layers and stacks of layers.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Besides binding kinetics, MP-SPR can also provide information on structural changes in terms of layer true thickness and refractive index.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] MP-SPR has been applied successfully in measurements of lipid targeting and rupture, CVD-deposited single monolayer of graphene (3.7Å) as well as micrometer thick polymers.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The most common data interpretation is based on the Fresnel formulas, which treat the formed thin films as infinite, continuous dielectric layers.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This interpretation may result in multiple possible refractive index and thickness values.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Usually only one solution is within the reasonable data range.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In multi-parametric surface plasmon resonance, two SPR curves are acquired by scanning a range of angles at two different wavelengths, which results in a unique solution for both thickness and refractive index.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Metal particle plasmons are usually modeled using the Mie scattering theory.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In many cases no detailed models are applied, but the sensors are calibrated for the specific application, and used with interpolation within the calibration curve.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Due to the versatility of SPR instrumentation, this technique pairs well with other approaches, leading to novel applications in various fields, such as biomedical and environmental studies.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When coupled with nanotechnology, SPR biosensors can use nanoparticles as carriers for therapeutic implants.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] For instance, in the treatment of Alzheimer's disease, nanoparticles can be used to deliver therapeutic molecules in targeted ways.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In general, SPR biosensing is demonstrating advantages over other approaches in the biomedical field due to this technique being label-free, lower in costs, applicable in point-of-care settings, and capable of producing faster results for smaller research cohorts.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In the study of environmental pollutants, SPR instrumentation can be used as a replacement for former chromatography-based techniques.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Current pollution research relies on chromatography to monitor increases in pollution in an ecosystem over time.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When SPR instrumentation with a Kretschmann prism configuration was used in the detection of chlorophene, an emerging pollutant, it was demonstrated that SPR has similar precision and accuracy levels as chromatography techniques.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Furthermore, SPR sensing surpasses chromatography techniques through its high-speed, straightforward analysis.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] One of the first common applications of surface plasmon resonance spectroscopy was the measurement of the thickness (and refractive index) of adsorbed self-assembled nanofilms on gold substrates.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The resonance curves shift to higher angles as the thickness of the adsorbed film increases.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This example is a 'static SPR' measurement.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When higher speed observation is desired, one can select an angle right below the resonance point (the angle of minimum reflectance), and measure the reflectivity changes at that point.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This is the so-called 'dynamic SPR' measurement.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The interpretation of the data assumes that the structure of the film does not change significantly during the measurement.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] SPR can be used to study the real-time kinetics of molecular interactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Determining the affinity between two ligands involves establishing the equilibrium dissociation constant, representing the equilibrium value for the product quotient.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This constant can be determined using dynamic SPR parameters, calculated as the dissociation rate divided by the association rate.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] In this process, a ligand is immobilized on the dextran surface of the SPR crystal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Through a microflow system, a solution with the analyte is injected over the ligand-covered surface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The binding of the analyte to the ligand causes an increase in the SPR signal (expressed in response units, RU).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Following the association time, a solution without the analyte (typically a buffer) is introduced into the microfluidics to initiate the dissociation of the bound complex between the ligand and analyte.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] As the analyte dissociates from the ligand, the SPR signal decreases.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] From these association ('on rate', *k*a) and dissociation rates ('off rate', *k*d), the equilibrium dissociation constant ('binding constant', *K*D) can be calculated.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The detected SPR signal is a consequence of the electromagnetic 'coupling' of the incident light with the surface plasmon of the gold layer.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This interaction is particularly sensitive to the characteristics of the layer at the gold–solution interface, which is usually just a few nanometers thick.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] When substances bind to the surface, it alters the way light is reflected, causing a change in the reflection angle, which can be measured as a signal in SPR experiments.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] One common application is measuring the kinetics of antibody-antigen interactions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] As SPR biosensors facilitate measurements at different temperatures, thermodynamic analysis can be performed to obtain a better understanding of the studied interaction.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] As SPR allows real-time monitoring, individual steps in sequential binding events can be thoroughly assessed when investigating the suitability between antibodies in a sandwich configuration.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Additionally, it allows the mapping of epitopes as antibodies of overlapping epitopes will be associated with an attenuated signal compared to those capable of interacting simultaneously.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Recently, there has been an interest in magnetic surface plasmons.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] These require materials with large negative magnetic permeability, a property that has only recently been made available with the construction of metamaterials.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Layering graphene on top of gold has been shown to improve SPR sensor performance.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Its high electrical conductivity increases the sensitivity of detection.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] The large surface area of graphene also facilitates the immobilization of biomolecules while its low refractive index minimizes its interference.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Enhancing SPR sensitivity by incorporating graphene with other materials expands the potential of SPR sensors, making them practical in a broader range of applications.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] For instance, the enhanced sensitivity of graphene can be used in conjunction with a silver SPR sensor, providing a cost-effective alternative for measuring glucose levels in urine.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Graphene has also been shown to improve the resistance of SPR sensors to high-temperature annealing up to 500 °C.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Recent advancements in SPR technology have given rise to novel formats, increasing the scope and applicability of SPR sensing.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] Fiber optic SPR involves the integration of SPR sensors into the optical fibers, enabling the direct coupling of light with the surface plasmons as light is passed through the hollow SPR core, and the analyte is behind a thin metal sheet surrounding the hollow core.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This format offers enhanced sensitivity and allows for the development of compact sensing devices, making it particularly valuable for applications requiring remote sensing in the field.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] It also offers an increased surface area for analytes to bind to the inner lining of the fiber optic.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] SPR curves usually show a strong minimum.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] With the use of a combined chromium-gold film or other carefully chosen material combinations a sharp resonance maximum can be observed when exciting a surface plasmon in the Kretschmann configuration.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/surface-plasmon-resonance] This may be useful in sensors applications where a strong and sharp resonance above noise is required and less heat is desired at the surface.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] A **thermal shift assay** (**TSA**) measures the stability of a protein by the change in its thermal denaturation temperature.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This is done under varying conditions, such as variations in drug concentration, buffer formulation (pH or ionic strength), redox potential, or sequence mutation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The most common method for measuring protein thermal shifts is differential scanning fluorimetry (DSF).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] DSF methodology includes techniques such as nanoDSF, which relies on the intrinsic fluorescence from native tryptophan or tyrosine residues, and Thermofluor, which utilizes extrinsic fluorogenic dyes.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The binding of low molecular weight ligands can increase the thermal stability of a protein, as described by Daniel Koshland (1958) and Kaj Ulrik Linderstrøm-Lang and Schellman (1959).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Almost half of enzymes require a metal ion co-factor.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermostable proteins are often more useful than their non-thermostable counterparts, e.g., DNA polymerase in the polymerase chain reaction, so protein engineering often includes adding mutations to increase thermal stability.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Protein crystallization is more successful for proteins with a higher melting point and adding buffer components that stabilize proteins improve the likelihood of protein crystals forming.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] If examining pH then the possible effects of the buffer molecule on thermal stability should be taken into account along with the fact that pKa of each buffer molecule changes uniquely with temperature.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Additionally, any time a charged species is examined the effects of the counterion should be accounted for.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermal stability of proteins has traditionally been investigated using biochemical assays, circular dichroism, or differential scanning calorimetry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Biochemical assays require a catalytic activity of the protein in question as well as a specific assay.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Circular dichroism and differential scanning calorimetry both consume large amounts of protein and are low-throughput methods.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The Thermofluor assay was the first high-throughput thermal shift assay and its utility and limitations has spurred the invention of a plethora of alternate methods.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Each method has its strengths and weaknesses but they all struggle with intrinsically disordered proteins without any clearly defined tertiary structure as the essence of a thermal shift assay is measuring the temperature at which a protein goes from well-defined structure to disorder.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] nano-Differential scanning fluorimetry, or nanoDSF, is a biophysical characterization technique used for assessing the conformational stability of a biological sample, typically a protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Samples are subjected to either temperature ramps or gradients of chemical denaturant, and the intrinsic fluorescence is measured and fit to determine the melting point (*T*m).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Applications include formulation ranking, protein engineering (comparing mutants to wild type), and ligand binding (quantification of affinity constants).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] A prerequisite of the technique is that the protein must contain an intrinsically fluorescent residue, typically tryptophan or tyrosine residues.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Benefits include tag-free analysis, avoidance of extrinsic fluorophores, low sample consumption, easy of use, amenity to automation, and high screening throughput.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Drawbacks include a propensity for false positives and negatives, usually necessitating follow-up screening with a potentially lower-throughout orthogonal technique to confirm.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Current commercial instruments employ either proprietary capillaries or generic high-throughput 384-well plates for sample analysis.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The technique was first described by Semisotnov et al.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] (1991) using 1,8-ANS and quartz cuvettes.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] 3 Dimensional Pharmaceuticals were the first to describe a high-throughput version using a plate reader and Wyeth Research published a variation of the method with SYPRO Orange instead of 1,8-ANS.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] SYPRO Orange has an excitation/emission wavelength profile compatible with qPCR machines which are almost ubiquitous in institutions that perform molecular biology research.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The name differential scanning fluorimetry (DSF) was introduced later but Thermofluor is preferable as Thermofluor is no longer trademarked and differential scanning fluorimetry is easily confused with differential scanning calorimetry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] SYPRO Orange binds nonspecifically to hydrophobic surfaces, and water strongly quenches its fluorescence.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] When the protein unfolds, the exposed hydrophobic surfaces bind the dye, resulting in an increase in fluorescence by excluding water.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Detergent micelles will also bind the dye and increase background noise dramatically.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This effect is lessened by switching to the dye ANS; however, this reagent requires UV excitation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The stability curve and its midpoint value (melting temperature, *T*m also known as the temperature of hydrophobic exposure, *T*h) are obtained by gradually increasing the temperature to unfold the protein and measuring the fluorescence at each point.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Curves are measured for protein only and protein + ligand, and Δ*T*m is calculated.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The method may not work very well for protein-protein interactions if one of the interaction partners contains large hydrophobic patches as it is difficult to dissect prevention of aggregation, stabilization of a native folds, and steric hindrance of dye access to hydrophobic sites.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In addition, partly aggregated protein can also limit the relative fluorescence increase upon heating; in extreme cases there will be no fluorescence increase at all because all protein is already in aggregates before heating.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Knowing this effect can be very useful as a high relative fluorescence increase suggests a significant fraction of folded protein in the starting material.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This assay allows high-throughput screening of ligands to the target protein and it is widely used in the early stages of drug discovery in the pharmaceutical industry, structural genomics efforts, and high-throughput protein engineering.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Compound solutions: Test ligands are prepared at a 50- to 100-fold concentrated solution, generally in the 10–100 mM range.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] For titration, a typical experimental protocol employs a set of 12 wells, comprising 11 different concentrations of a test compound with a single negative control well.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Protein solution: Typically, target protein is diluted from a concentrated stock to a working concentration of ~0.5–5 μM protein with dye into a suitable assay buffer.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The exact concentrations of protein and dye are defined by experimental assay development studies.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Instrumental set up: A typical temperature ramp rates range from 0.1 to 10 °C/min but generally in the range of 1 °C/min.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The fluorescence in each well is measured at regular intervals, 0.2–1 °C/image, over a temperature range spanning the typical protein unfolding temperatures of 25–95 °C.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] (2008) published a variation on the Thermofluor assay where SYPRO Orange was replaced by *N*-[4-(7-diethylamino-4-methyl-3-coumarinyl)phenyl]maleimide (CPM), a compound that only fluoresces after reacting with a nucleophile.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] CPM has a high preference for thiols over other typical biological nucleophiles and therefore will react with cysteine side chains before others.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Cysteines are typically buried in the interior of a folded protein as they are hydrophobic.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] When a protein denatures cysteine thiols become available and a fluorescent signal can be read from reacted CPM.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The excitation and emission wavelengths for reacted CPM are 387 nm/ 463 nm so a fluorescence plate reader or a qPCR machine with specialized filters is required.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Alexandrov et al. used the technique successfully on the membrane proteins Apelin GPCR and FAAH as well as β-lactoglobin which fibrillates on heating rather than going to a molten globule.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The DSF-GTP (GFP-Tagged Protein-of-Interest) technique was developed by a team led by Patrick Schaeffer at James Cook University and published in Moreau et al.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] These techniques are limited by their requirement for both highly purified proteins and solvatochromic dyes, prompting the need for more robust high-throughput technologies that can be used with crude protein samples.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This need was met with the development of a new high-throughput technology for the quantitative determination of protein stability and ligand binding by differential scanning fluorimetry of proteins tagged with green fluorescent protein (GFP).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This technology is based on the principle that a change in the proximal environment of GFP, such as unfolding and aggregation of the protein of interest, is measurable through its effect on the fluorescence of the fluorophore.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The technology is simple, fast and insensitive to variations in sample volumes, and the useful temperature and pH range is 30–80 °C and 5–11 respectively.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The system does not require solvatochromic dyes, reducing the risk of interferences.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The protein samples are simply mixed with the test conditions in a 96-well plate and subjected to a melt-curve protocol using a real-time thermal cycler.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The data are obtained within 1–2 h and include unique quality control measures through the GFP signal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] DSF-GTP has been applied for the characterization of proteins and the screening of small compounds.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] 4-(dicyanovinyl)julolidine (DCVJ) is a molecular rotor probe with fluorescence that is strongly dependent on the rigidity of its environment.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] When protein denatures, DCVJ increases in fluorescence.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] It has been reported to work with 40 mg/ml of antibody.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The lifetime of tryptophan fluorescence differs between folded and unfolded protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Quantification of UV-excited fluorescence lifetimes at various temperature intervals yields a measurement of *T*m.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] A prominent advantage of this technique is that no reporter dyes need be added as tryptophan is an intrinsic part of the protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This can also be a disadvantage as not all proteins contain tryptophan.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Intrinsic fluorescence lifetime works with membrane proteins and detergent micelles but a powerful UV fluorophore (e.g. auto-fluorescent small molecule) in the buffer could drown out the signal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Utilization of the intrinsic fluorescence properties of tryptophan residues in many proteins forms the basis of nanoDSF.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The emission wavelengths of tryptophan residues are dependent on the surrounding chemical environment, notably solvation (see solvatochromism) and therefore differ between folded and unfolded protein, just as with the fluorescence lifetime.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Typically, interior tryptophan residues in a more hydrophobic environment exhibit a notable emission red shift from approximately 330 nm to 350 nm upon protein unfolding and exposure to water.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Quantification of fluorescence wavelength shifts at various temperature intervals yields a measurement of *T*m.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Currently there are at least three instruments on the market that can read this shift in wavelength in a high-throughput manner while heating the samples.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The advantages and disadvantages are the same as for fluorescence lifetime except that there are more examples in the scientific literature of use. nanoDSF uses the intrinsic fluorescence of tryptophan residues present in many proteins to monitor protein folding and stability.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Because tryptophan fluorescence depends on the local chemical environment, protein unfolding exposes buried residues to water and typically shifts the emission maximum from about 330 nm to 350 nm.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Static light scattering allows monitoring of the sizes of the species in solution.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Since proteins typically aggregate upon denaturation (or form fibrils) the detected species size will go up.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This is label-free and independent of specific residues in the protein or buffer composition.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The only requirement is that the protein actually aggregates/fibrillates after denaturation and that the protein of interest has been purified.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In fast parallel proteolysis the researcher adds a thermostable protease (thermolysin) and takes out samples in parallel upon heating in a thermal gradient cycler.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Optionally, for instance for proteins expressed at low levels, a western blot is then run to determine at what temperature a protein becomes degraded.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] For pure or highly enriched proteins, direct SDS-PAGE detection is possible facilitating Commassie-fluorescence based direct quantification.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] FastPP exploits that proteins become increasingly susceptible to proteolysis when unfolded and that thermolysin cleaves at hydrophobic residues which are typically found in the core of proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] To reduce the workload, western blots could be replaced by SDS-PAGE gel polyhistidine-tag staining, provided that the protein has such a tag and is expressed in adequate amounts.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] FastPP can be used on unpurified, complex mixtures of proteins and proteins fused with other proteins, such as GST or GFP, as long as the sequence that is the target of the western blot, e.g., His-tag, is directly linked to the protein of interest.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] However, commercially available thermolysin is dependent on calcium ions for activity and denatures itself just above 85 degrees Celsius.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] So calcium must be present and calcium chelators absent in the buffer - other compounds that interfere with the function (such as high concentrations of detergents) of the protease could also be problematic.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] FASTpp has also been used to monitor binding-coupled folding of intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs).
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Cellular thermal shift assay (CETSA®) is a biophysical technique applicable on living cells as well as tissue biopsies.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] CETSA® is based on the discovery that protein melting curves can also be generated in intact cells and that drug binding leads to very significant thermal stabilization of proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Upon denaturation, proteins are aggregated and can thus be removed by centrifugation after lysis of the cells.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The stable proteins are found in the supernatant can be detected; e.g., by western blot, alpha-LISA, or mass spectrometry.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The CETSA®-technique is highly stringent, reproducible, and not prone to false positives.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] However, it is possible for a sample, or small molecule compound, to bind a protein in a given target's pathway.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] If that protein induces further stabilization of the original target protein through a cascade event, it could manifest as direct target engagement.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] An advantage of this method is that it is label-free and thus applicable for studies of drug binding in a wide range of cells and tissues.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] CETSA® can also be conducted on cell lysates versus intact cells, helping to determine sample penetration of the cell membrane.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor variant specific for flavin-binding proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Analogous to Thermofluor binding assays, a small volume of protein solution is heated up and the fluorescence increase is followed as function of temperature.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In contrast to Thermofluor, no external fluorescent dye is needed because the flavin cofactor is already present in the flavin-binding protein and its fluorescence properties change upon unfolding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Size exclusion chromatography can be used directly to access protein stability in the presence or absence of ligands.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Samples of purified protein are heated in a water bath or thermocycler, cooled, centrifuged to remove aggregated proteins, and run on an analytical HPLC.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] As the melting temperature is reached and protein precipitates or aggregates, peak height decreases and void peak height increases.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This can be used to identify ligands and inhibitors, and optimize purification conditions.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] While of lower throughput than FSEC-TS, requiring large amounts of purified protein, SEC-TS avoids any influence of the fluorescent tag on apparent protein stability.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In fluorescence-detection size exclusion chromatography the protein of interest is fluorescently tagged (e.g., with GFP) and run through a gel filtration column on an FPLC system equipped with a fluorescence detector.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The resulting chromatogram allows the researcher to estimate the dispersity and expression level of the tagged protein in the current buffer.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Since only fluorescence is measured, only the tagged protein is seen in the chromatogram.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] FSEC is typically used to compare membrane protein orthologs or screen detergents to solubilize specific membrane proteins in.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] For fluorescence-detection size-exclusion chromatography-based thermostability assay (FSEC-TS) the samples are heated in the same manner as in FastPP and CETSA and following centrifugation to clear away precipitate the supernatant is treated in the same manner as FSEC.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Larger aggregates are seen in the void volume while the peak height for the protein of interest decreases when the unfolding temperature is reached.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] GFP has a *T*m of ~76 °C so the technique is limited to temperature below ~70 °C.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] GPCRs are pharmacologically important transmembrane proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Their X-ray crystal structures were revealed long after other transmembrane proteins of lesser interest.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The difficulty in obtaining protein crystals of GPCRs was likely due to their high flexibility.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Less flexible versions were obtained by truncating, mutating, and inserting T4 lysozyme in the recombinant sequence.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] One of the methods researchers used to guide these alterations was radioligand binding thermostability assay.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The assay is performed by incubating the protein with a radiolabelled ligand of the protein for 30 minutes at a given temperature, then quench on ice, run through a gel filtration mini column, and quantify the radiation levels of the protein that comes off the column.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The radioligand concentration is high enough to saturate the protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Denatured protein is unable to bind the radioligand and the protein and radioligand will be separated in the gel filtration mini column.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] When screening mutants selection will be for thermal stability in the specific conformation, i.e., if the radioligand is an agonist, selection will be for the agonist binding conformation and if it is an antagonist, then the screening is for stability in the antagonist binding conformation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Radioassays have the advantage of working with minute amounts of protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] But it is work with radioactive substances and large amount of manual labour is involved.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] A high-affinity ligand has to be known for the protein of interest and the buffer must not interfere with the binding of the radioligand.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Other thermal shift assays can also select for specific conformations if a ligand of the appropriate type is added to the experiment.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor has been extensively used in drug screening campaigns.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Because Thermofluor detects high affinity binding sites for small molecules on proteins, it can find hits that bind to active site subsites, cofactor sites, or allosteric binding sites with equal efficacy.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The method typically requires the use of screening compound concentrations at >10x the desired binding threshold.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Setting 5 μM as a reasonable hit threshold consequently requires a test ligand concentration of 50 to 100 μM in the sample well.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] For most drug compound libraries, where many compounds are not soluble beyond ~100 μM, screening multiple compounds is consequently not feasible owing to solubility issues.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor measurements of *T*m can be quantitatively related to drug *K*d values, although this requires the additional calorimetric measurements of the target proteins' enthalpy of unfolding, determined using DSC.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The dynamic range of the Thermofluor assay is very large, so that the same assay can be used to find micromolar hits and to optimize sub-nanomolar leads, making the method particularly useful in the development of QSAR relationships for lead optimization.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Many proteins require the simultaneous or sequential binding of multiple substrates, cofactors, and/or allosteric effectors.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor studies of molecules that bind to active site subsites, cofactor sites, or allosteric binding sites can help elucidate specific features of enzyme mechanism that can be important in the design of effective drug screening campaigns and in characterizing novel inhibitory mechanisms.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor pre-screens can be performed that sample a wide range of pH, ionic strength, and additives such as added metal ions and cofactors.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The generation of a protein response surface is useful for establishing optimal assay conditions and can frequently lead to improved purification scheme as required to support HTS campaigns and biophysical studies.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Many applications of protein engineering for drug discovery or biophysics applications involve modification of the protein amino acid sequence through truncation, domain fusions, site-specific modifications or random mutagenesis.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Thermofluor provides a high throughput method for the evaluation of the effects of such sequence variations on protein stability as well as means for developing stabilizing conditions if required.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Although proteins are dynamic structures in solution, formation of protein crystals is expected to be favored when all molecules lie in their lowest energy conformation.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Since Thermofluor is a label-free assay that detects small molecule binding to high affinity binding sites on a target protein, it is well suited to finding small molecule inhibitors of protein-protein interactions or allosteric modulation sites.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Of course, whether or not a protein-protein interaction is ultimately "druggable" with a small molecule requires the presence of a suitable binding site on the target protein that provides enough local energetic interactions to allow specific drug binding.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Membrane proteins are often isolated in the presence of hydrophobic solubilizing agents that can partition hydrophobic-binding dyes like 1,8-ANS and SYPRO orange and generate a fluorescence background that obscures observation of a Thermofluor protein melting signal.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The biochemical function of protein targets identified through gene knockout or proteomics approaches are often obscure if they have low amino acid sequence homology with proteins of known function.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In many cases some useful information can be gained through the identification of binding cofactors or substrate analogs in classifying protein function, information useful in using Thermofluor can assist in "decrypting" the function of proteins whose biochemical function might otherwise be unknown.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Recent developments have extended thermal shift approaches to the analysis of ligand interactions in complex mixtures, including intact cells.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Initial observations of individual proteins using fast parallel proteolysis (FastPP) showed that stabilization by ligand binding could impart resistance to proteolytic digestion with thermolysin.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Protection relative to reference was quantified through either protein staining on gels or western blotting with a labeling antibody directed to a tag fused to the target protein.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] CETSA, for cellular thermal shift assay, is a method that monitors the stabilization effect of drug binding through the prevention of irreversible protein precipitation, which is usually initiated when a protein becomes thermally denatured.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] In CETSA, aliquots of cell lysate are transiently heated to different temperatures, following which samples are centrifuged to separate soluble fractions from precipitated proteins.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] The presence of the target protein in each soluble fraction is determined by western blotting and used to construct a CETSA melting curve that can inform regarding in vivo targeting, drug distribution, and bioavailability.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Both FastPP and CETSA generally require antibodies to facilitate target detection, and consequently are generally used in contexts where the target identity is known a priori.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] Newer developments seek to merge aspects of FastPP and CETSA approaches, by assessing the ligand-dependent dependent proteolytic protection of targets in cells using mass spectroscopy (MS) to detect shifts in proteolysis patterns associated with protein stabilization.
[src:fragment-based-drug-discovery/thermal-shift-assay] This would be a major advance for drug discovery since it would allow the identification of discrete molecular targets (as well as off-target interactions) for drugs identified through high-content cellular or phenotypic drug screens.
